4. Having someone else login if needed; The platform has to decide how to handle this. They can allow multiple user profiles allowed on the same account with individual typing patterns per profile or maybe allow other 2FA methods like OTP.

3b. You have specified for password reset which is short text in general. In this case, you have to enroll the typing pattern again on the new password. To let him do that, you can ask for his previous password+typing pattern or fall back on another 2FA option.

3a. TypingDNA can authenticate a person if they type something different than what was enrolled(a.k.a any text) but it applies for longer texts and enrollment text is by default different than for authentication.. See https://www. typingdna.com/demo-anytext.h tml …

2. People have different behavior when they type on a physical keyboard than on virtual. Cross-platform compatibility is not supported at this point but what is supported is typing pattern recorded and matched for each type of device individually for the same person.

1. In order for a randomness to work on a key logged password, it would have to be calibrated to fool the matching algorithm for that specific person. Until you reach that calibration, you already get flagged and can't try again.

There is software to alter your typing speed so that your typing pattern is protected. Just Google it. You can also hide your fingerprint and you face to avoid those biometrics verification but you eventually use the real one when you need it for real.

The extension doesn't look at everything you type. It just looks at how you type (actual content is not recorded in a TypingDNA typing pattern, btw) your credentials to access the 2FA codes. That's it. It can't see typing activity outside of the app itself.
